<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Reaffirms Necessity of Albright's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Jordan reaffirmed today the
necessity of U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright's
upcoming Middle East trip and gave it an optimistic assessment.
</P>
<P>
Minister of State for Information Affair Samir Mutawe said at
today`s cabinet meeting that "we hope that Albright will go ahead
with her visit because of the very serious consequences" incurred
by Thursday`s suicide bombings in West Jerusalem which killed seven
people and injured 190 others.
</P>
<P>
To facilitate the secretary`s maiden trip to the region, King
Hussein of Jordan will attend a tripartite summit with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
Sunday in Cairo to deal with the latest developments in the
region, Mutawe said.
</P>
<P>
"The (U.S.`s) very determination of going ahead with the
visit is an indication that the U.S. is now (still) active in
playing its role as a partner in making the peace process
works," he added.
</P>
<P>
The minister also said that Jordan is optimistic about
Albright`s visit which is scheduled for Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton said after the suicide bombings
that Albright would go ahead next week with her planned trip to
the Middle East despite the attack.
</P>
<P>
The main aim of Albright's trip will be to rebuild diminishing
confidence between Israel and the Palestinians following months
of stalemate in the peace process which has been stalled since
Israel began construction of new Jewish settlements in Arab East
Jerusalem in March this year.
</P>
<P>
Albrigt's tour will include Israel, Palestinian-held
territory, Egypt, Jordan, Syria and Saudi Arabia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
