<HEADLINE> CIS Countries Sign Papers on Frontier Defenses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 6 (Xinhua) -- The Commonwealth of Independent
States (CIS) countries have signed a series of documents on
cooperation in defending their frontiers.
</P>
<P>
The documents were signed at the 26th meeting of the CIS
Frontier Force Commander Committee, which was held in the
Kirgizstan resort of Cholpon-ata, about 240 kilometers east of the
Kyrgyz capital. The meeting ended today, the Itar-Tass and
Inter-fax news agencies reported.
</P>
<P>
These documents concern enhanced cooperation between CIS and
non-CIS countries in monitoring the activities of border
transiting and the exchange of information among CIS countries.
</P>
<P>
The papers are subject to the approval of the CIS summit.
</P>
<P>
The 12-member CIS, established in 1991 when the former Soviet
Union collapsed, groups all former Soviet republics except for the
three Baltic countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
