<HEADLINE> Southern African Teachers Work out Science </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 6 (Xinhua) -- More than 20 teachers from
southern African states are attending a two-day regional workshop on
science across Africa which opened here today.
</P>
<P>
The workshop is expected to come up with a position paper on
science in Africa which will be presented at the Science Across
the World Workshop to be held in Washington in November.
</P>
<P>
Science Across Africa is a project sponsored by BP Shell
International, which involves in promoting science outside the
laboratory among high school students.
</P>
<P>
More than 4,000 students in the SADC (Southern African
Development Community) are taking part in the project which is
also found in Europe, Asia-Pacific and the Americas.
</P>
<P>
Margaret Rutherford, project co-ordinator, said the aim of the
project is to encourage students to observe and learn science in
the the community they live.
</P>
<P>
"The idea is to teach the children to identify any scientific
happenings in the society," she said.
</P>
<P>
Opening the workshop, Zimbabwean Education, Sports and Culture
Minister Gabriel Machinga said taht a lot of changes were taking
place in science and Africa could not afford to lag behind.
</P>
<P>
He urged the participants to come up with a position paper
relevant to the needs of the continent.
</P>
<P>
The participants are from Namibia, Swaziland, South Africa,
Zambia and Zimbabwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
