<HEADLINE> 3 Farmers Killed in Southern Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Three farmers were killed today
by suspected militants while working in corn fields in Upper
Egypt, the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
An Interior Ministry official said the farmers were shot and
axed to death by the militants at Rawdah village, Malawi, about
250 kilometers south of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
The gunmen managed to flee, according to the agency.
</P>
<P>
In a separate incident, a policeman was wounded in a shoot-out
with militants who escaped in a stolen car, in Atqa village in
Malawi, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Upper Egypt has become the key stronghold of Egypt's main armed
Islamic group, the Al Gamaa Islamiya in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
This group has been leading a militant campaign to topple the
secular government since 1992, in which more than 1,180 people,
mostly policemen and militants, have been killed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
