<HEADLINE> Namibia Denies Reported Financial Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 6 (Xinhua) -- The Namibian government
today denied reports that it is facing a financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
South African Broadcasting Association today quoted Isack
Kaulinge, Secretary to the Namibian cabinet, and Usutuaije
Maamberua, permanent secretary to the Ministry of Finance, as
saying.
</P>
<P>
"There was no fiscal crisis on hand and the Namibian
government was not heading for bankruptcy," they said.
</P>
<P>
The two officials made the denial following a report by the
privately-owned newspaper, the Namibian.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper claimed that the Namibian government's budget
deficit to have shot up to around 20-million U.S. Dollars because
of uncontrolled spending by ministries.
</P>
<P>
The report, based on a memorandum sent out by the National
Planning Commission, called for austerity measures to ensure the
government adhere to budgeted fiscal deficit.
</P>
<P>
The Namibian government has budgeted for a deficit of 3.91
percent during the 1997-98 financial year, but it now stands at
12 percent of gross domestic product. 
</P>
</TEXT>
