<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Studies to Curb Diseases in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 6 (Xinhua) -- The World Health
Organization (WHO) today noted that many diseases affecting
Africa today could have been prevented if appropriate information
and communication materials were used.
</P>
<P>
WHO made the assessment in a report released at a meeting of
African Health Ministers, which just concluded in Sun City, about
200 km northwest of Pretoria, South Africa's administrative
capital.
</P>
<P>
The study said although health information has been made use
of over the past 30 years, results have not matched the efforts.
</P>
<P>
The experts said the failure constitutes a serious handicap to
the promotion of health and the attainment of the goal of health
for all.
</P>
<P>
The document criticised what it called gaps in the design,
production, delivery, use and effectiveness of health
information, stressing that a gap existed between people with
information and persons who needed it.
</P>
<P>
Language is another barrier in the use of information
materials, the document added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
