<DOCNO> XIE19970907.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt, Jordan Call for Saving Oslo Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Egypt and Jordan said today a
tripartite Arab summit will be convened Sunday to discuss the
crisis in the Mideast and save Oslo accord, the cornerstone of the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak today invited King Hussein of
Jordan and Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President Yasser
Arafat to a summit meeting here Sunday for consultations on the
latest developments of the Mideast peace process, especially on
the Palestinian-Israeli peace track.
</P>
<P>
"The summit aims at finding ways to salvage the peace drive,
especially its terms of reference, based on the land-for-peace
principle and abidance of both parties by the Oslo agreement and
negotiations on various issues including security," Egyptian
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Following the summit, Mubarak will hold contacts with a number
of Arab leaders, as the tripartite summit will be based on the
Arab references expressed in the June 1996 Arab summit
resolutions, namely peace is an Arab option, he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is clear that the situation is critical in the occupied
territories and the Mideast peace process," Moussa said,
explaining the reason behind the convocation of the summit.
</P>
<P>
"What matters is the implementation of the agreement and not
just reconsidering them," Moussa said, in response to the latest
Israeli decision not to withdraw from new areas in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu declared Friday
that Oslo will soon be buried and ruled out handing over more land
to Palestinians until Arafat cracked down on Muslim militants in
the wake of Thursday's triple suicide bombings in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has held the PNA "indirectly responsible" for the
attacks, the second in the city in five weeks, and reimposed a
complete closure on the West Bank and Gaza Strip, which had been
eased earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
Israel has withdrawn its troops, handing over much of the Gaza
Strip and parts of the West Bank to Palestinian self-rule under
peace deals with Arafat starting in 1993. It is supposed to
withdraw from more of the West Bank by mid-1998.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Jordanian Ambassador to Egypt and Jordan's permanent
delegate to the Arab League Nayef Saud Al Qadi stressed the
importance of the tripartite summit.
</P>
<P>
Al Qadi said that talks among the three leaders will focus on
boosting the peace process and salvaging the staggered peace
process.
</P>
<P>
The peace process was in fact in a very bad situation even
before the Jerusalem blasts due to Israeli practices, especially
the erection of settlements and non commitment to signed
agreements, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, it is important now to save the peace process which
is facing many challenges, he emphasized.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peacemaking has been in crisis since
last March over Jewish settlement construction in East Jerusalem
which the Palestinians want as part of a future state.
</P>
<P>
The stalemate has been deepened by the suicide attacks, first
on July 30 when 15 Israelis were killed by two suicidal bombs in a
Jerusalem market and the second on Thursday that killed six people
and wounded 192. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
