<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-06 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Envoy Holds Talks with Iranian Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 6 (Xinhua) -- A special envoy of the European
Union (EU) held talks with an Iranian official here today in an
attempt to solve the four-month diplomatic crisis between both
sides, the Iranian official news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The agency, however, did not give the name and nationality of
the envoy, only said he arrived here Friday night.
</P>
<P>
The envoy met with Ali Ahani, Iranian Foreign Ministry official
in charge of West European Affairs, according to the agency.
</P>
<P>
The two officials conferred on Iran-EU current state of
relations, as well as the proposed meeting of the foreign
ministers of EU's Troika members with Iranian Foreign Minister
Kamal Kharrazi on the sidelines of the upcoming U.N. General
Assembly in New York, the report said.
</P>
<P>
But Iran expressed doubts over the possibility of holding such
meetings and their fruitfulness in case the EU countries'
embassies in Tehran do not resume normal activities prior to the
U.N. General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Iranian government sources even claimed that Iran was not in a
hurry to have the ambassadors of EU members return to Iran.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian evening paper Kayhan reported today that the EU
special envoy came here in "an attempt to bring about a return of
European ambassadors to Tehran."
</P>
<P>
All the EU countries, except Greece, recalled their ambassadors
home from Tehran after a German court last April implicated top
Iranian leaders in the killing of three Kurdish dissidents and
their translator in Berlin in 1992.
</P>
<P>
As a measure to punish Iran, EU also decided not to hold
ministerial meetings between any of its member state and Iran.
</P>
<P>
Tehran has insisted that the German ambassador be at the tail
of any return by EU envoys to Iran -- a condition Germany views as
an unacceptable "divide and conquer" tactic.
</P>
<P>
Iran's new president, 54-year-old moderate cleric Mohammad
Khatami who was sworn in office on August 4 after a landslide
victory, has signaled a new era in Tehran's attitude to foreign
relations, calling for an "active and fresh presence."
</P>
</TEXT>
