<HEADLINE> Iran to Produce 140 Tonnes of Caviar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Iran said today that it would
produce 140 tonnes of caviar by the end of the current Iranian
year ending on March 20, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Mohammad Qassemi, Director General of Mazandaran Provincial
Fisheries Organization, said that 852 fishermen were busy catching
Beluga fish in Caspian Sea's southern coast.
</P>
<P>
He said that about 8 million Beluga roes are to be poured into
the Caspian Sea this year.
</P>
<P>
Iranian caviar is a product of the southern coast of the
Caspian Sea which has an ideal environment for sturgeon fish.
</P>
<P>
Unpolluted and healthy nature, appropriate depth of water,
temperate climate, traditional method of fishing together with
precise processing by skilled and experienced caviar processors
create the famous Iranian caviar of high quality.
</P>
<P>
Ninety percent of the world's caviar come from three different
Caspian Sea sturgeon fishes: Beluga, Asetra, and Sevrouga. Caviar,
energetic and delicious foodstuff, became famous as the "black
pearl of the Caspian Sea."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
