<HEADLINE> Canadian Exchanges to Beef Up Internet Policing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Canada's stock exchanges are
beefing up their policing of stock promotion on the Internet,
following a similar move by the U.S. stock market Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
Canada's largest stock exchange, the Toronto Stock Exchange
(TSE), has announced a two-phase plan to step up its surveillance
of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
The first phase is a software program that will take all the
"usenet" discussion groups the exchange receives on its server and
send them to its market surveillance department, using a filter
that highlights TSE-listed stocks.
</P>
<P>
That phase should be in place before the end of the year,
according to Rob Cook, TSE's director of market surveillance.
</P>
<P>
"In phase two, we'll get a Web crawler to look for new
information appearing on Web sites, related to TSE-listed stocks,"
he was quoted by a report today as saying.
</P>
<P>
The move by the TSE came as Nasdaq had said it would be
increasing its policing of the Internet through a search engine,
which is designed to patrol the internet for illegal hyping of
4,000 Nasdaq-listed companies.
</P>
<P>
The new tool will be programmed with a series of stock phrases
such as "Invest now! You'll double your money in two months" --
phrases people have been using.
</P>
<P>
Nasdaq's new search engine is expected to be put into use
before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Gerry Romanzin, an Alberta Stock Exchange spokesman, said five
market surveillance staff there spend up to two hours each a day
surfing the Net.
</P>
<P>
"It's a common area of concern amongst all exchanges," he
noted.
</P>
<P>
The British Columbia Securities Commission said it is also
looking at specialized search engines to police the Internet stock
promotion.
</P>
<P>
Yet, one Canadian regulator conceded that the fight against
stock promotion on the Internet will be very difficult.
</P>
<P>
"We're regulators with a finite amount of resources and it's
tough to keep up," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
