<HEADLINE> SADC Summit to Focus on Economic Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BLANTYRE, Malawi, September 6 (Xinhua) -- The forthcoming
summit of the Southern African Development Community (SADC) will
focus on economic integration in the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
The summit, to be held on the coming Monday, will try to map
out plans to integrate the southern African sub-region into a
common market, as is its goal for the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The sub-regional organization will stress on closer economic
ties within the sub-region, with a unified development policies,
which will faciliate their economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Information exhange, enhancement of techonological capacity,
common standards, environment protection, occupational health and
safety and the promotion of private sector participation which
are included in the protocols approved at SADC ministers'
conference, will be submitted to the summit.
</P>
<P>
Five new protocols on education, gender, industry, mining and
water are expected to be signed at the summit.
</P>
<P>
The utilization of modern information communication
techonology to inform the world about the positive changes taking
place in the region will be a topic for discussion at the summit,
Alfred Nzo, Chairman of SADC's Ministeral Council, said at a
press conference Friday.
</P>
<P>
A "univisas" system for free tours among the member states is
to be discussed at the Blantyre summit so to promote personnel
exchange and enhance tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
Also on the agenda will be the mineral industry, which was
witnessing a decline in recent years in the resource-rich
sub-region. Importance will be attached to the harmonization of
national and regional policies, strategies and programs related
to the development and exploitation of mineral resources.
</P>
<P>
The SADC summit will work to maintain a sustainable economic
development through closer cooperation among its 12 member
states, while searching for ways to co-ordinate with other
economic and political organizations in Africa and the world in
general, such as the Organization of African Unity (OAU), the
Common Market for Eastern and Southern Afria, African Development
Bank and European Union.
</P>
<P>
The summit will review the applications of the Democratic
Republic of Congo and the Seychelles, for joining the regional
grouping.
</P>
<P>
The 12 SADC members are Angola, Botswana, Lesetho, Malawi,
Mauritius, Mozambique, Namibia, South Africa, Swaziland,
Tanzania, Zambia, and Zimbabwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
