<HEADLINE> Viruses Crowd Saskatchewan Wetlands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Two Canadian scientists have
discovered that wetlands and ponds in the province of Saskatchewan
have one of the highest concentrations of viruses in the world.
</P>
<P>
The count of 2.5 billion viruses per milliliter of water
astounded the two scientists, said a report today.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Richard Robarts of Environment Canada's National Hydrology
Research Institute and Prof. David Bird of the University of
Quebec said that more research is required to determine the nature
of viruses.
</P>
<P>
The findings are not likely to have serious implications for
human or animal health, the scientists said. Rather, they fit an
emerging picture of an invisible but extraordinary active part of
most aquatic ecosystems.
</P>
<P>
Previous research found high concentrations of viruses in
marine water -- about 10 million per milliliter of water.
</P>
<P>
The latest findings appear to show that other aquatic systems
are just as virally active as the oceans, said Prof. Curtis Suttle
at the University of British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
"We are filling the picture. Viruses are not only extremely
important in the oceans, but in lakes and ponds and sediments.
Basically they are everywhere we look," Prof. Suttle said.
</P>
<P>
The scientists believed that it would be alarmist to raise
questions about the quality of drinking water in the prairie
province.
</P>
<P>
"There is no relationship between the abundance of viruses in
the environment and the abundance of animal pathogens," Prof.
Suttle added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
