<HEADLINE> Kenyan Situation Peaceful and Stable: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap
Moi today stressed that situation in kenya is peaceful and stable,
criticizing continuous negative reports about Kenya and its
leadership by foreign journalists.
</P>
<P>
These foreign journalists enjoyed the peace, security and
other modern facilities available here which cannot be found in
the troubled spots of Africa they wrote about, said the
73-year-old Moi who has been in power for 19 years.
</P>
<P>
They described the eastern African country as being in chaos,
Moi charged. More than 150 foreign correspondents are based in
Nairobi currently.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he called on his ruling Kenya African National
Union (KANU) and the opposition to make efforts to maintain peace
and development in the country, saying a coalition of parties
will promote tribalism and scare away potential investors.
</P>
<P>
Moi made the remarks at the national gathering where more than
845 million Shillings (13.6 million U.S. Dollars) were donated by
all walks of life to assist Kenya's women development programs.
</P>
<P>
The money will be distributed fairly and accordingly to all
provinces, Moi assured.
</P>
<P>
Also today, the inter-parties parliamental group completed its
technical work on minimum constitutional reforms which will have
some so-called oppressive laws on public security and election
repealed or revised, the Kenya TV Network (KTN) reported tonight.
</P>
<P>
Seventeen foreign embassies here, mainly from western
countries, have announced their support for the work of the
13-member parliamental group, formed by KANU and the opposition
jointly, said the report.
</P>
<P>
However, the opposition umbrella body National Convention
Executive Council (NCEC) has dismissed the group's talks and
called national strikes and demonstrations to press the
government for total constitutional reforms before the general
election.
</P>
<P>
The strikes and demonstrations have been scheduled for
September 17,18, and October 8,9, NCEC senior member Willy
Mutunga said Thursday. He said that rallies are also to be held
in Kisumu, Kenya's third-largest city, on Sunday, and in Nairobi
on October 10, a public holiday.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 parliamental members held a meeting last
Thursday and resolved to form a 13-member inter-parties
parliamentary body to replace NCEC to spearhead reforms talks
between KANU and the opposition.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, KANU reiterated it will not hold dialogue with the
NCEC as the latter is unregistered, insisting that the reforms
talks should only be undertaken within legal framework.
</P>
<P>
KANU will open its National Delegate Conference on September
16 over reform talks and the forthcoming general elections. At a
KANU conference before the first multi-party election in 1992,
Moi was elected as KANU's sole presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
Political atmosphere has been tightening in the country
following several rounds of violent clashes between the
government and the opposition since May, the key loan cut by the
International Monetary Fund and killings on the Coast Province.
</P>
<P>
Moi said that he would soon announce the poll date. 
</P>
