<HEADLINE> Exhibition Serve As Window for Progressing Heilongjiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 7 (Xinhua) -- An ongoing exhibition titled
"Glorious Five Years" has given spectators a complete picture of
the economic growth and social progress in China's northermost
Heilongjiang Province since 1992.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition, which opened Saturday in Beijing, outlines the
economic advances in Heilongjiang through photographs and words.
</P>
<P>
The province scored 240.26 billion yuan in its gross domestic
product in 1996, a rise of 41.7 percent over five years ago,
seeing an annual growth rate of 9.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
With the application of more advanced technology in farming,
the province has been one of China's major commodity grain
production bases, and the total grain output reached 30.47 billion
kilograms last year.
</P>
<P>
The animal husbandry in the region has also developed rapidly,
according to the exhibition, which shows that the province now has
970,000 cows, ranking first in the country.
</P>
<P>
Heilongjiang, as the country's old base of energy, forestry,
and mechanical and electronics industries, is hurrying to improve
the competitiveness of its products.
</P>
<P>
The Daqing Oilfield's success in using hi-tech in oil
exploitation and its annual output of crude oil have provided more
than 50 million tons over the past successive 21 years.
</P>
<P>
Petrochemicals, electronics, food processing and
pharmaceuticals have become new pillar industries in the region,
while forestry and coal industries are working to improve their
sagging profits.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition shows that Heilongjiang has forged closer ties
with the outside world by opening 25 ports, and its foreign trade
volume in bordering areas has ranked first in China, seeing 6.3
billion US dollars in the 1992-96 period. It also introduced 7.1
billion yuan in funding from other provinces and cities.
</P>
<P>
In the cultural sphere, artists in Heilongjiang province have
been encouraged to take searches into their heritage for
inspiration, and as a result 14 dramas have won national prizes.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
