<HEADLINE> North China Province to Speed Up Development of Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, September 7 (Xinhua) -- North China's Shanxi Province
will speed up development of its scenic resources to make tourism
its pillar industry, a provincial official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Han Heping, deputy director of the Provincial Tourism Bureau,
told members of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference (CPPCC) National Committee from the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region, who are on an inspection tour of the
province, that Shanxi has more than 50 renowned tourist
attractions including Wutai Mountain, the Yungang Grottoes and the
Hukou Waterfall, in addition to its 31,401 ancient buildings.
</P>
<P>
Han said that tourism has been listed as one of Shanxi's key
industries in the next 15 years so as to turn the province into a
well-known tourist attraction in north China.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the province has 44 travel agencies with
more than 60,000 employees. Till now, 800,000 overseas tourists
and 63 million domestic travelers have visited the province.
</P>
<P>
The province earned 2.75 billion yuan (335 million US dollars)
from tourism last year.
</P>
<P>
Han said that with the rapid development of transportation,
communication and the hotel industry, the province will receive
more tourists in the future.
</P>
<P>
Shanxi has opened eight special tourist routes and held several
celebration activities to mark the 1997 China Tourist Year.
</P>
</TEXT>
