<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-07 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Rebukes Call for Unilateral S. Lebanese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu today rejected the call for a unilateral
pullout from South Lebanon, where 13 Israeli soldiers were killed
in the past week.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu was making the statement this morning at the weekly
Cabinet meeting attended by senior defense officials to discuss
the situation in South Lebanon, especially the Friday incident
that killed 12 Israeli soldiers and stunned the army as well as
the whole nation.
</P>
<P>
A special Israeli naval squad was ambushed by Hezbollah forces
early Friday near a village between Sidon and Tyre while on their
way to carry out a raid mission. Eleven commandos were killed,
another soldier went missing, presumed dead, and four others
wounded in the fierce fighting.
</P>
<P>
This morning, one more Israeli soldier was killed when
Hezbollah gunmen shelled Israeli outposts in the eastern sector
of the Israeli-proclaimed South Lebanon security zone.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu ruled out an immediate unilateral withdrawal from
South Lebanon despite the recent disaster and blamed politicians
from the opposition for calling for such a pullout.
</P>
<P>
He said such a call would only hurt the troops stationed in
South Lebanon, while encouraging the Hezbollah by "adding oil
into the engines of Hezbollah rockets."
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu also criticized some government officials for
disclosing the details of the discussions on South Lebanon during
the emergency security Cabinet meeting held on Friday.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the meeting discussed several options
presented by Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, including
reducing Israeli military presence and carrying out unilateral
withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
The latest tragedy has heated up the debate on Israel's
continued military presence in South Lebanon, at a time when the
nation was caught in grief over the triple suicide bombings
Thursday in a central Jerusalem pedestrian mall that killed seven
people and wounded 190 others.
</P>
<P>
Since Israel established the so-called South Lebanon Security
Zone in 1985, its troops have been bogged down in a cruel
guerrilla war with Muslim guerrilla forces fighting to liberate
South Lebanon from Israeli occupation.
</P>
<P>
So far there have been 219 Israeli soldiers killed in South
Lebanese fightings, excluding the 73 killed in February this year
when two transport helicopters collided.
</P>
<P>
Following Friday's incident, the opposition Labor party's
lawmaker Yossi Beilin once again called for the government to
pull out troops unilaterally and unconditionally from South
Lebanon. He said Israel can be far better defended behind a good
fence along the northern border.
</P>
<P>
Beilin is organizing a multi-party campaign to push for the
unilateral withdrawal from South Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
However, other lawmakers disagreed with Beilin's view. Labor
lawmaker Ephraim Sneh criticized Beilin's remarks as "shameful
defeatism." The ruling Likud party's lawmaker Uzi Landau warned
that "disasters ought not be exploited to further pet political
projects."
</P>
<P>
The Leftist Meretz party leader Yossi Sarid also disagreed
with Beilin, saying a unilateral withdrawal would only bring
terrorist groups along the northern border. He said a deal was
needed with Syria, which is regarded by Israel as the main sponsor
of Hezbollah forces.
</P>
<P>
Labor's leader Ehud Barak convened a party meeting today to
discuss the Lebanese issue. Former prime minister Shimon Peres
echoed Sarid's view that the only way to solve the South Lebanon
problem was through conducting negotiations with Syria in order
to reach a peace agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
