<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Oil Industry Registers Rapid Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 7 (Xinhua) -- China's petroleum industry
made a big leap forward in the 1991-1996 period, increasing output
from 137 million tons to 141 million tons. The country is now the
fifth largest oil producer in the world.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Yongkang, president of China National Petroleum
Corporation, the biggest state-owned oil company, which turns out
90 percent of the country's crude oil and 86 percent of its
natural gas, said that a stable output was maintained in the
oilfields in eastern China during the past five years.
</P>
<P>
The Daqing Oilfield, the largest in China, for instance, has
kept an annual output of more than 50 million tons for 21 years
running.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the development of the oil industry was in full
swing in the west. Annual output of crude oil increased
from 7.02 million tons to 14.33 million tons in the Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region, northwest China.
</P>
<P>
An additional three billion tons of oil were found in Xinjiang
during the past five years, largely easing the shortage of energy
sources there, the president said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the country explored 606 billion cubic meters of
natural gas reserves, and increased the gas output to 16.44
billion cubic meters in 1996, 1.33 billion cubic meters more than
the 1992 figure.
</P>
<P>
Two natural gas pipelines, one connecting the north of Shaanxi
Province and Beijing, and the other running from Shanshan to
Urumqi in Xinjiang, has gone into operation, supplementing the
energy supply in northern China.
</P>
<P>
The oil refining capacity of the country was doubled during the
last five years, hitting 28.4 million tons annually. Last year
China refined a total of 18.2 millions of crude oil, Zhou said.
</P>
<P>
China has clinched 36 oil projects with other countries since
1991, attracting 790 million US dollars in foreign fund. So far,
21 provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions have approved
foreign-funded petroleum projects.
</P>
<P>
Also, China has signed seven oil exploration contracts with
Peru, Sudan, Venezuela and Kazakhstan, and will get 12 million
tons of oil by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Zhou said his company generated 145 billion yuan (17.7 billion
US dollars) in petroleum and natural gas sales last year, and made
8.96 billion yuan (1.1 billion US dollars) in profit.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
