<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Americans Win Men's Eights World Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The United States won the men's
eight at the rowing world championships in Aiguebelette, France,
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
With four gold medals, including the two most prestigious
men's titles -- the eight and the men's singles sculls -- the
Americans took second place in the nations' standings behind
Germany, who won five events.
</P>
<P>
Romanians took the second place with Australia finishing
strongly to take third.
</P>
<P>
The American crew of Garrett Miller, Robert Cummins, Timothy
Richter, Bob Kaehler, Michael Wherley, Philipe Henry, Sebastian
Bea, Christian Ahrens and cox Peter Cippolone clocked an
impressive 5:27.20 on a foggy day in the French Alps.
</P>
<P>
The Romanian women's eight, Olympic champions in Atlanta,
were again untouchable in their class, beating Canada by 4.78
seconds and Britain by 7.60.
</P>
<P>
Italia's foursome Giovanni Calabrese, Rossano Galtarossa,
Agostino Abbagnale and Alessandro Corona, reclaimed the title of
the quadruple scull they won in the world championships in 1994
and 1995.
</P>
<P>
Germany's victories on Sunday came in the women's lightweight
double sculls, lightweight quadruple sculls and quadruple sculls.
</P>
<P>
Hosts France won their second gold of the championships on
Sunday in the men's coxed four.  
