<DOCNO> XIE19970907.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-07 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab Leaders Urge Intensified Efforts to Save </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The leaders of Egypt, Jordan
and the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) today called on
Washington to double its efforts to salvage the jeopardized peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, Jordan's King Hussein and
PNA President Yasser Arafat issued the call in a released
statement at the end of their two-and-half-hour urgent meeting
here, convened to coordinate their stance before the first trip
to the Mideast by U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright this
week.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak greeted Hussein and Arafat at the airport this morning
and accompanied them directly to his palace. They did not speak
to reporters and seemed to avoid making any predictions about
Albright's multi-leg trip that include Israel, the Palestinian
self-rule areas, Jordan, Egypt, probably Syria and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
The three Arab leaders welcomed the upcoming tour of Albright
to the region and expressed hope for its success.
</P>
<P>
Albright is expected to revive the Palestinian-Israeli
peacemaking that has been in crisis since March over Jewish
settlement construction on land the Palestinians want as part of
a future state.
</P>
<P>
The stalemate has been deepened by the suicide attacks in
Jerusalem, first on July 30 when two human bombs killed 15
Israelis and now on last Thursday when seven were killed by a
triple bombing attack.
</P>
<P>
The three leaders condemn terrorism and the use of violence
targeting innocent civilians and said that violence runs
contrary to the spirit of peace, according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, they urged for taking measures to help the parties
directly concerned with the conflict, to transcend the current
stalemate and escape the crisis that threatened the region and
the whole international community.
</P>
<P>
"The three leaders called on the world community in general
and the forces that play a major role in sponsoring the Middle
East peace process in particular, to intensify efforts and double
their interests to confront the dangers to the peace process,"
said the statement.
</P>
<P>
They stressed that people in the Mideast have to be aware that
peace is their "unnegotiable strategic option of no return" and
take viable measures to avoid creating any new obstacles in the
future.
</P>
<P>
The three leaders called for fully implementing the signed
agreements and avoiding unilateral decision that contradicted the
spirit of peace.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Jordan are the only two Arab countries that have
diplomatic ties with Israel and played important roles in past
mediation.
</P>
<P>
The three Arab leaders met in the aftermath of a triple
suicide bombing in Jerusalem Thursday and the tight Israeli
closure of Palestinian areas.
</P>
<P>
Israel has held the PNA "indirectly responsible" for the
attacks, the second in the city in five weeks, and reimposed a
complete closure on the West Bank and Gaza Strip which had been
eased earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
After the bombing, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
Friday ruled out handing over more land to Palestinians until
Arafat cracked down on Muslim militants, accusing him of failing
to honor a commitment under interim peace accords to fight
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Israel has redeployed its troops, handing over much of the
Gaza Strip and parts of the West Bank to Palestinian self-rule
under peace deals with Arafat starting in 1993. It is supposed to
withdraw from more of the West Bank by mid-1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
