<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Residents Cast Eyes on Congress  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 7 (Xinhua) -- With just five days to go
before the opening of the 15th National Congress of the Communist
Party of China (CPC), Beijing residents are eagerly anticipating
the event designed to set China's social and economic development
course for the future.
</P>
<P>
Streets and alleys of the capital city are decked out with
flowers, billowing flags and colorful bunting to greet the
meeting, which is to start on September 12 as proposed by the
Political Bureau of the CPC Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
At the Tian'anmen Square, horticulturists and gardeners are
arranging all kinds of potted flowers and creating artificial
landscapes, and onlookers and tourists stop to take photographs.
</P>
<P>
Among them was a retired cadre named Xue Minggui in his early
sixties, who was taking a picture of his grandson. "Every resident
can witness the great expansion of all businesses during the
course of the reform and opening-up, which were first launched in
the late 1970s," he said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, He said he hopes that the congress will further build
up the people's confidence in the country's successful march along
the road charted by Deng Xiaoping.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has approved a total of 12,000 foreign-funded
enterprises over the past two decades, with a combined contractual
investment of 20 billion US dollars from overseas, according to Yi
Xiqun, director of the Beijing Municipal Commission on Foreign
Trade and Economic Relations.
</P>
<P>
He said he hoped that China will accelerate its reform and
opening-up pace after the congress and that Beijing, too, will
open still wider to the outside world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
