<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Residents Cast Eyes on Congress  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
People from all walks of life have placed great hopes on the
congress. "I hope my life will continue to be improved," said Niu
Shengbin, a former farmer is now working as a civil engineer, With
his annual income increased year by year, he has bought a
refrigerator, a color TV, and a washing machine, and has deposited
tens of thousands yuan in the bank.
</P>
<P>
On top of that, he was given a two-room new apartment from his
work unit last year.
</P>
<P>
Various department stores and food markets are crowded with
shoppers. At the Di'anmen Food Market, a housewife holding a
basket full of fresh vegetables and fish said, "Speaking of
changes over the past five years, the greatest change is in my
basket, which has been growing heavier and heavier. I hope our
government at all levels will concentrate more on practical
matters," she added.
</P>
<P>
Though it's the weekend, students at the prestigious Beijing
University got down to the business of studying and attending
lectures. Many classrooms are filled with students.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Weimin, director of the university publicity department,
said, "As a educator, I am impressed by the strategy of building
up the nation through science and education and I hope the
congress will carry out this strategy further and give still
greater prominence to education."
</P>
<P>
Sun Zhe, associate professor of Qinghua University, expressed
his confidence in China's future, saying that "the convocation of
the CPC 15th National congress will surely promote China's
economic and political structural reforms and uplift the country's
material and socialist ethical and cultural progress." 
</P>
</TEXT>
