<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of India's Bombay Stock Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Share prices staged a fresh
rally at the Bombay Stock Exchange (BSE) market during the past
week on hectic short-covering and speculative buying by investors
and financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
The rally was bolstered by the Indian government's decision to
replace the administered price mechanism on petroleum products
with a market determined pricing policy.
</P>
<P>
The sustained recovery lifted the sensitive index back to cross
the 4,000-mark level, registering a gain of 156 points during the
week.
</P>
<P>
Market sources said the decision to scrap the administered
price mechanism on petroleum products was a step in the right
direction and the recovery in the share prices would now raise the
index to around 4,500 level by the end of October.
</P>
<P>
During the week under review, the sensitive index ended with a
gain of 156.27 points at 4,032.35. The BSE-100 ended at 1,755.40
with a gain of 60.44 over the last weekend close of 1,694.76.
</P>
<P>
The BSE-200 improved by 12.28 points to 392.32 and the dollex
by 4.64 to 178.66 from their last week close of 380.04 and 174.02
respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
