<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai's New Pudong Area Seeks Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Pudong, formerly a remote,
backward corner in the metropolis of Shanghai, which emerged as a
major development zone in the early 1990s, is working to attract more
overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, the local government also hopes to increase
earnings from tourism. Local policymakers hope to transform the
rapidly developing district into a dreamland for both domestic and
overseas tourists.
</P>
<P>
The local New Pudong Area Administration recently
recommended four new tours and listed 15 tourism projects for
domestic and overseas investment.
</P>
<P>
According to officials, tourists can now visit Asia's tallest
tower, the Orient Pearl TV Tower, and the nation's largest stock
exchange.
</P>
<P>
Tourists can also visit hundreds of garden-like modern factories
and office buildings in Pudong's four development zones, and view
the Bund on the opposite side of the Huangpu River, an area
featuring centuries-old western-style highrises.
</P>
<P>
Other attractions include a wildlife zoo, a park exhibiting the
unique lifestyles of ethnic groups in China, the Huaxia Tourist
City, and an aquarium.
</P>
<P>
The 15 proposed investment projects include a forest nature
reserve, a holiday resort, a coastal cable-car project, the World
Park, a seashore sports ground, a floral park, the Seashore Health
World, a recreational center, the Shanghai Historic Wax Museum, a
sports park, a festival park, a holiday farm project, and a forest
bathing zone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
