<HEADLINE> China's Actual Overseas Investment Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The actual use of overseas
investment has gone up by 1.49 percent in the first half of this
year, though the number of newly-approved foreign-funded firms and
contractual foreign investment plunged notably.
</P>
<P>
The two figures plummeted to 9,753 companies and 22.81 billion
US dollars, down 30.64 percent and 50.01 percent respectively,
compared with the corresponding period of the last year.
</P>
<P>
The statistics were presented at today's news conference on the
upcoming '97 China Investment and Trade Talks, which will be held
in Xiamen, Fujian Province in east China.
</P>
<P>
According to official numbers, by the end of June this year,
China had approved 293,573 overseas-financed enterprises, with a
contractual foreign investment of 492.2 billion US dollars and an
actual overseas investment of 197.2 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Currently, about 230,000 of these firms are in operation, while
21,000 have halted business and another 38,000 plan to do the
same, citing lack of operating funds and technological
support. according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is still the largest overseas investor, accounting
for 49.63 percent of the total overseas investment, down from 51
percent in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
