<DOCNO> XIE19970907.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-07 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Receives Most Contracted Food Supplies: UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has received some 75
percent of the food supplies contracted in the first stage of the
oil-for-food deal with the United Nations, a U.N. official has
said.
</P>
<P>
Local daily "Babel" today quoted the U.N. Coordinator for
Humanitarian Affairs in Iraq Eric Valt as saying that Iraq has
received a total of 1.7 million tonnes of food and other essential
needs since the deal came into force last December.
</P>
<P>
But he said only 20 million U.S. dollars worth of medicines, or
10 percent of the amount Iraq is entitled to import during the
same stage, has arrived in the U.N. sanction-ridden country.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement which allows Iraq to sell oil for buying
food and medicine, Iraq is entitled to import 804 million dollars
worth of food and 210 million dollars worth of medicines during
the first six-month stage of the deal.
</P>
<P>
Another 1 billion dollars earned from oil sale is earmarked for
the needs of water, electricity, education and farming sectors
which also run short under the U.N. sanctions imposed after Iraq's
invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The deal has been renewed for another six months, but the
second stage has seen no arrival of newly-contracted food supplies
due to some disagreements between Baghdad with the UN. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
