<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Killed by Land-mine in Somali Town </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, September 7 (Xinhua) -- At least three people were
killed and five others wounded when a land mine exploded on a
Toyota pickup truck belonging to forces of Hussein Mohamed Aidid,
12 km west of Huddor town, Saturday.
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here today said the truck was transporting
10 armed militiamen heading for Dhiil village where Hussein
Aidid's men were maintaining a militia base since the worst
battle against the rahanwein resistance army (RRA) took place on
August 14.
</P>
<P>
A RRA spokesman admitted that his forces have planted a number
of land mines for what he called defensive purposes against the
forces of leader of south Mogadishu faction Hussein Aidid.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman Mohamed Ali Aden Qalinle put the number of the
fatalities by the land mine to more than eight.
</P>
<P>
Qalinle today repeated his warning against the use of the
roads within bay and bakol regions by the civilians and ngos,
saying his forces have again cut off the road linking Dinsor and
Burhakaba towns of Bay region.
</P>
<P>
He declined to say whether his forces have also planted land
mines on this important road which has been widely used for the
commercial activities between Baidoa and Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
As the hit and run guerrilla fighting by the RRA forces have
been on halt these days, the land mine planting campaign seems to
be posing hazards to the forces of Hussein Aidid in the regions
of Bay and Bakol southwest of Somalia.
</P>
<P>
According to reports from Huddor town, another lorry mounted
with a towing machine and a double barrel anti-aircraft machine
gun has narrowly escaped an explosion of a land mine which only
destroyed the rear part of the vehicle, but claimed no lives of
its occupants.
</P>
<P>
These hazards are taking place at a time when peace
initiatives encouraged by Hussein Aidid are continuing in the
regions of Bay and Bakol since the beginning of this month. A
delegation led by Sheikh Mukhtar Mohamed Hussein, the spokesman
of Somalia's first civilian parliament, and officials from
Hussein Aidid's self-styled government are meeting elders from
the different communities of Rahanwein.
</P>
<P>
RRA representatives have characterized these peace efforts as
nonsense. Qalinle said there can be no peace in these regions as
long as Hussein Aidid's men are in control of Bay and Bakol
regions.
</P>
<P>
Qalinle claimed that Sheikh Mukhtar cannot bring about peace
since he admitted that he's not independent for his moves and
decisions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
