<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cableway for Sacred Taoist Mountain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, September 7 (Xinhua) -- A cableway was recently
completed on Mount Wudang, a sacred Taoist mountain in
central China's Hubei Province.
</P>
<P>
The cableway has set two records in China: its height from the
beginning to the ending point is 645 meters and the span between
two of its pillars reaches 365 meters.
</P>
<P>
The 1,500-meter cableway, funded by two local companies, was
built at a cost of some 30 million yuan (3.6 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The cableway extends from Qiongtai, a scenic site on the
mountain's rear slope, to the peak known as Jingding.
</P>
<P>
Mount Wudang, a famous tourist site and original home of the
Chinese martial art of "Wudang Boxing", was placed on the UNESCO
list of cultural heritages in 1994. Some one million people
visited the mountain in 1996 alone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970907.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Namibia Pays Tribute to Mother Teresa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Namibia today joined
millions of mourners across the world to pay tribute to Mother
Teresa of the Missionaries of Charity who died in Calcutta, India
Friday.
</P>
<P>
"She was an illuminating light that lit our souls with hope as
humans," South African Press Association quoted Namibian Foreign
Minister Theo-ben Gurirab as saying in Windhoek, the capital of
Namibia.
</P>
<P>
Gurirab described last week, which also claimed the life of
Diana, Princess of Wales, as one of major devastation.
</P>
<P>
Diana died in a car crash in Paris on August 31. She was 36.
</P>
<P>
"There is a strange coincidence in that two of the
extraordinary devotees of the world's poor, needy and dying should
have died in the same week.
</P>
<P>
"One was a tall, stunning beauty of great warmth, immense
glamor and wealth. The other was in rags, tiny, unattractive,
unassuming and virtually invisible," Gurirab said.
</P>
<P>
"One would think of Mother Teresa as the tallest tree in the
fauna of humanity," he said of the Roman Catholic nun who has
devoted the last 50 years caring for the sick, dejected unwanted
and dying.
</P>
<P>
"As Namibians, government, community and individuals, we would
want to join the multitudes of mourners all over the world as we
pay tribute to Mother Teresa who was a living saint among us," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
