<HEADLINE> Jiangsu Builds World's Largest Reserve for David's Deer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, September 7 (Xinhua) -- East China's Jiangsu Province
has built the world's largest natural reserve for David's Deer,
local officials said.
</P>
<P>
Dafeng Natural Reserve, the only one for the protection of
David's Deer in China, now has 302 such animals living in over
78,000 hectares of woodland, grassland and marshland.
</P>
<P>
The number of David's Deer is still on the rise by an annual
rate of some 23 percent, according to the official in charge of
the reserve.
</P>
<P>
He said that more than five million yuan (600,000 US
dollars) has been invested in the reserve, and the local
government has decided to give another 78,000 hectares of beach
land this year to enlarge the deers' living space.
</P>
<P>
Scientists said that seven research projects have been carried
out since the reserve was established in 1986. On the basis of the
research, they have obtained a wealth of data and statistics about
the natural conditions needed for the breeding of David's Deer.
</P>
<P>
Origninally, David's Deer was a rare animal in China. But it
disappeared in the country in 1900.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the joint efforts by the World Wide Fund and the
Chinese Ministry of Forestry, 39 David's Deers were brought back
to their homeland from Britain in 1986. 
</P>
</TEXT>
