<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chiluba Stresses Need to Protect Strategic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- President Frederick Chiluba
today stressed the need to protect Zambia's strategic sectors
from "unfair competition" arising from imported goods, according
to Zambia News Agency ZANA.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba made the remarks at the Lusaka International Airport
here shortly before his departure for Blantyre, Malawi to attend
the annual summit scheduled Monday of the Southern African
Development Community (SADC). He is accompanied by the First Lady
and six ministers of the government.
</P>
<P>
There is need to give priority to sectors like agriculture and
manufacturing to prevent them from collapsing under stiff
competition from imported goods, said the president, while
explaining his country does not wish to take a "protectionist"
stand.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba complained that Zambia is sometimes used as a "dumping
ground" by others. Therefore, the country wants to "level the
playing field", he said.
</P>
<P>
However, the Zambian president didn't say what measures Zambia
is going to take to protect its strategic sectors.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, Zambia declared a ban on importation of wheat
flour, which is aimed at promoting local wheat milling.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the integration of the SADC, Chiluba said Zambia
is consistent and will continue to fight for the removal of trade
barriers which is the key to the achievement of regional economic
integration.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his hope that the SADC members will double their
efforts to remove the barriers and allow the free flow of
investment.
</P>
<P>
The SADC, which was founded in 1992 and groups 12 countries,
is struggling for the integration of the regional economy.
</P>
<P>
The SADC summit to be held Monday is expected to review, among
other issues, the body's program of action in various sectors
such as agriculture, food and natural resources, mining, human
resources, employment and labor as well as trade tariffs.
</P>
</TEXT>
