<HEADLINE> Ramos Says His Option Is to Endorse Successor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel
Ramos said today that what he meant by keeping his options open
includes endorsing his successor from the ruling party for next
year's elections.
</P>
<P>
Ramos caused public anxieties when he announced last week that
he was keeping his options open -- a remark interpreted by many as
a statement that Ramos was planning for re-election if amendments
are made to the constitution.
</P>
<P>
"Now, what are the options that I am talking about which has
created a lot of unhappiness..., the President has options,
including actions for the endorsement of a presidential candidate
under the banner of the majority party..." Ramos told reporters
today in Mabalacat, the Northern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Ramos also denied that his administration is planning to impose
martial law in the country in order to extend his term.
</P>
<P>
He appealed for calm and sobriety in the face of rumors, saying
that speculative statements "can only undermine efforts to sustain
the country's economic gains and political stability."
</P>
<P>
Under the Philippine Constitution, Ramos is only allowed to
serve a single six-year term, and must step down in June next
year.
</P>
<P>
But opposition parties are accusing the Ramos administration of
creating instability by planting bombs in cities and using
explosion incidents as an excuse to impose martial law in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Last Thursday, two separate bomb blasts in Manila killed six
people and wounded over 60 others.  
</P>
</TEXT>
