<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Travelers Check Expected in December </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 7 (Xinhua) -- ECOWAS travelers check, a
monetary instrument designed to facilitate economic integration
in west Africa, is expected to be launched at the end of this
year.
</P>
<P>
The move is widely regarded by economic watchers as a prelude
to monetary integration and the eventual adoption of a single
west African currency by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The Committee of Governors of Central Banks of the Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS) is scheduled to meet in
December to give a final touch for the launching.
</P>
<P>
The measure will enhance intra-community payments as a means
of boosting regional transactions.
</P>
<P>
To achieve the goal of a single monetary zone by the turn of
the century, ECOWAS leaders have established an ad hoc monitoring
committee, comprising the heads of state of Cape Verde, Cote
d'Ivoire, Ghana, Mali and Togo.
</P>
<P>
On the basis of technical reports and proposals submitted to
it, the committee would give periodical policy direction and new
orientations to facilitate compliance by member states with
agreed monetary and financial targets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
