<HEADLINE> Blair Sees Improving Britain As Way to Remember Diana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Britain can better remember
Diana, Princess of Wales, by becoming a better place, British
Prime Minister Tony Blair said today.
</P>
<P>
"Let her legacy be compassion. Let us be a better, a more
compassionate Britain," Blair said in a BBC television interview.
</P>
<P>
He said that there was a tremendous desire for the death of the
Princess to be given lasting significance.
</P>
<P>
The funeral of Diana, who died on August 31 in a car crash in
Paris, was held on Saturday morning in London's Westminster Abbey.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Blair gave his backing to a permanent memorial for
Diana, saying Chancellor of the Exchequer Gordon Brown was to head
a committee on how the government might help with the memorial.
</P>
<P>
He also confirmed that he had seen a role for Diana as a
special ambassador for Britain before her death.
</P>
<P>
Diana had confided in an interview with The New Yorker that
Blair had wanted her to go on "mission" for Britain and she
believed Blair knew how to deploy her skills.
</P>
<P>
Blair also said much of last week's criticism of the royal
family was "very unfair", adding that the question throughout the
week had been what was best for Prince William and Prince Harry.
</P>
<P>
He said the media needed to "learn some lessons" from the death
of Diana about "the boundaries of proper conduct." 
</P>
</TEXT>
