<DOCNO> XIE19970907.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Higher Input Prices, Misuse of Fertilizer Hurt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Input price hikes and haphazard
use of fertilizers are hurting Bangladesh's agriculture and the
government should take measures to ensure the efficient
application of technology in the sector, a local newspaper said
today.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture is the mainstay of the South Asian country's
economy and it accounts for about 37 percent of the GDP, though
that share will decline as industrial incomes and employment rise.
</P>
<P>
The agriculture's development, however, is now being curbed by
input price hikes, unplanned use of chemical fertilizers and
insecticides in farmland as well as inefficiency in applying
technology, the Independence newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
With the overwhelming majority of the population -- 87
percent-- living in the rural areas, and over half of them living
below the poverty line, no growth and poverty alleviation strategy
for Bangladesh can succeed without a healthy agricultural sector,
the newspaper stressed.
</P>
<P>
A special study report of the World Bank entitled "Bangladesh:
Agenda for Action, 1996" underlines the fact that the vast
majority of the Bangladesh population depend on agriculture and
natural resources for a large part of their food and incomes, the
paper noted.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi government has already given serious attention
to the grave situation in the agriculture and its budgetary
allocations had been made to subsidize the agricultural sector,
the paper said.
</P>
<P>
What is needed more urgently appears to be applying appropriate
and affordable technologies to ensure sustainable growth of the
sector, the newspaper said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970907.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NAM Cultural Ministers Pledge to Enhance Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTA FE DE BOGOTA, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Non-Aligned
Movement (NAM) Cultural Ministers today pledged to strengthen
cultural cooperation among NAM member countries, aiming at
maintaining the cultural diversity and promoting cultural
development.
</P>
<P>
This came in the "Declaration of Principles" and "Action Plan"
approved by the first conference of NAM cultural ministers closed
on Saturday in the Columbian city of Medellin.
</P>
<P>
Cultural ministers and senior officials from 53 NAM member
countries attended the three-day meeting which started on
September 4.
</P>
<P>
The meeting reiterated that the principles of the Non-Aligned
Movement are still in effect in times of economic globalization.
</P>
<P>
The Declaration pointed out that the globalization of economy,
the enlarged technology gaps between the north and the south, and
aggressions and occupations are threatening the cultures of
developing countries, as well as their sovereignty and
survival. Therefore, "Each nation's sovereignty and culture should
be respected on the basis of international law, international
human rights law and the United Nations Charter."
</P>
<P>
"International cultural relations should be based on
cooperation but not on confrontations," and "such cooperation
should be based on the recognition and respect for the unique
cultural properties and sovereignty of various peoples," the
Declaration said.
</P>
<P>
"The cultural diversity and viewing the world from a
multi-angle are beneficial to establishing a new world order," the
participants said.
</P>
<P>
The Declaration stressed that news media should play an
important role in promoting and defending the tolerance and
respect for the cultural diversity and the rights to cultural
development.
</P>
<P>
The Action Plan covers concrete proposals concerning the ways
on how to make new cultural policies, reserve cultural heritages,
promote education, enhance cultural cooperation and defend
cultural diversity.
</P>
<P>
Ministers and officials attending the meeting also agreed to
build a NAM cultural center in Cairo and a research institute in
Medellin. They decided to hold a NAM children and youth cultural
conference in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The decision to hold the conference of ministers of culture was
taken at the 11th Non-Aligned Movement Summit, which was held in
the Columbian city of Cartagena in 1995. The ministers' meeting
was the first of its kind since the establishment of the NAM in
1961. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970907.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DPRK, South Korea Re-open Aviation Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic People's Republic
of Korea (DPRK) and South Korea resumed their aviation talks
Sunday in Bangkok, Thailand, to discuss the opening of air passage
routes, the Construction and Transportation Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The talks, to last until Tuesday, are sponsored by the
International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO).
</P>
<P>
The two sides, having banned each other's flights from passing
through their skies since the division in 1945, had had several
rounds of meetings since last September.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to open their flight information regions (FIR) of
South Korea's southern city of Daegu and DPRK's capital Pyongyang
to all passenger flights.
</P>
<P>
But a full agreement has been delayed by differences on how to
set up a direct communication network between the two cities as
control transfer points.
</P>
<P>
Officials said South Korea has been trying to sign the pact as
soon as possible, because its national flag carrier will be able
to benefit from the accord by saving both time and costs.
</P>
<P>
Once the airspace is opened, South Korea's flights serving East
Asia, Northeast Russia and parts of the United States can shorten
their flight time by 20 to 47 minutes, said the officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
