<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China Province Attracts More Overseas Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, September 7 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong
Province has attracted 74.5 billion U.S. dollars in overseas funds
since 1978 when China opened its doors to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
Xu Dezhi, director of the Guangdong Provincial Committee of Foreign
Trade and Economic Cooperation, announced the figure during a
Wednesday ceremony marking the premier issue of a special edition
of "Guangdong Grand Economy and Trade" covering China's resumption
of sovereignty over Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Xu attributed Guangdong's rapid economic cooperation and
foreign trade growth to constantly expanding trade cooperation
between Guangdong and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
According to Xu, Hong Kong contributed some 70 percent of
Guangdong's overseas funding, including one third of the
province's total construction funds.
</P>
<P>
This year alone, some 80 percent of the province's foreign
trade was conducted via Hong Kong. Projections call for the
province's 1997 foreign trade volume to hit 120 billion
U.S. dollars, including exports of 65 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Xu added that Guangdong has drafted a long-term development
plan which calls for its import-export volume to hit 440 billion
U.S. dollars by the year 2010. 
</P>
</TEXT>
