<DOCNO> XIE19970907.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 1,700 Dealers Start Off-Floor Trading At SSE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 7 (Xinhua) -- More than 1,700 stock trading
companies from across China have started their off-floor business
at the Shanghai Stock Exchange (SSE), one of the only two bourses
in China.
</P>
<P>
Since April, the trading volume of these off-floor dealers has
surpassed that of floor traders.
</P>
<P>
Off-floor trading was initiated at the bourse on October 14,
1996, and since then, the number of SSE members who have applied
to join has reached over 95 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,700-some off-floor dealers, 344 are based in Shanghai,
which account for over 70 perceqt of the city's stock traders.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, 660 former floor members have withdrawn from SSE's
crowded trading hall.
</P>
<P>
All off-floor tradings, from any part of the country, can be
conducted through the market's computerized trading system.
</P>
<P>
The SSE authority issued a circular this May asking all its
members to supervise their own off-floor business so as to protect
the trading from unlawful practices.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the bourse has made a rule to keep copies of all
computer commands and trading results through two-way satellite
telecommunicational networks and other means. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
