<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Investment Funneling into Tianjin's State Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Tianjin, the largest port city
in north China, attracted 475 million US dollars of funds for its
state-run enterprises during the first half of the year, 17
percent up from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that more than 30 percent of the Chinese
industrial enterprises are struggling to drag themselves out of
the red into the black.
</P>
<P>
An offical in charge of the city's foreign investment affairs
said that the city's industry has 780 cooperative projects with
foreign investors, which have a total investment of 5.4 billion US
dollars. Two-thirds of the projects involve the city's state-owned
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, Tianjin lays special emphasis on
approving high-tech cooperation projects with foreigners, and the
average foreign investment scale for each project has reached 14
million US dollars, more than twice the figure 16 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Of the major projects is the joint venture between the Tianjin
Engine Works and Japan's Toyota Company. It has a total investment
of more than 260 million US dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
