<HEADLINE> Shanghai Financing Center Plays Bigger Role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The Shanghai Fund-Raising
Center, which was set up about nine years ago as a short-term
inter-bank loaning institution exclusively for local banking
bodies, has emerged as the largest of its kind in the country.
</P>
<P>
Over the past nine years, the financing center has played an
increasingly bigger role as its influence has reached the majority
of provinces, ethnic autonomous regions and major cities.
</P>
<P>
Local experts observe that the center has contributed a lot to
bolstering the flow of domestic capital and improving the
country's monetary market.
</P>
<P>
According to latest figures from the center, in the past five
and half years, it has dealt inter-bank loans amounting to 680.37
billion yuan, with most of the loans borrowed by institutions from
other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, its trading volume topped 178.4 billion yuan, a more
than fivefold increase over the figure for 1992. The amount was
82.84 billion yuan in the first half of this year, though the
city's capital supply was relatively rich during the period.
</P>
<P>
The fund-raising center is a member of the National Inter-Bank
System, which was put into operation in Shanghai early 1996.
</P>
<P>
Of the nine foreign bank branches in Shanghai approved for
conducting Renminbi yuan business, six have engaged in inter-bank
loan trading at the center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
