<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-07 09:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Envoy to Afghanistan Visits Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations envoy
to Afghanistan Lakhdar Ibrahimi is visiting Saudi Arabia in an
effort to find ways to end the Afghan civil war.
</P>
<P>
Ibrahimi arrived in the Saudi Red Sea coastal city of Jeddah
Saturday to continue his tour of countries concerned with the
prolonged conflict in Afghanistan, according to Kuwait News Agency
Kuna today.
</P>
<P>
Meeting chief of the Organization of Islamic Conference
Izzidine Al-Iraki in Jeddah today, Ibrahimi briefed him on the
results and details of his ongoing tour of Afghanistan and the
concerned states.
</P>
<P>
Ibrahimi had just finished visit to Afghanistan, Pakistan,
Russia and Tajikistan in search of a broad-based formula on ending
the protracted Afghan crisis.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. envoy is expected to meet with a number of Saudi
officials on Riyadh's position on the Afghan issue.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia is one of the major players in the Afghan
crisis. It had hosted a meeting of Afghan factions which resulted
in a Mecca declaration, bringing a short-lived peace to the
war-trodden Afghanistan people.
</P>
<P>
Quoting unidentified sources, Kuna said Ibrahimi may also hold
a meeting with Sheikh Mohammad Rabbani, prime minister of
Afghanistan's Taliban government, who is also in Saudi Arabia to
seek Saudi support.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia claimed it supports a peaceful settlement among
all warring factions in Afghanistan. But it was the second country
after Pakistan to give formal and immediate recognition to the
Taliban government in May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
