<HEADLINE> Egypt Vows to Continue War Against Militants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Interior Minister
Hassan el-Alfy has said that while he welcomed any attempts for
peace, he would continue to fight terrorism, local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press Saturday after inspecting admission
measures at the Police Academy, the minister again rejected the
idea of a dialogue with Egypt's biggest militant organization the
Islamic Group, saying that any breach of law would be decisively
dealt with.
</P>
<P>
"It is the mission of security bodies to maintain security and
law and not to make dialogue," el-Alfy said.
</P>
<P>
In response to a call made by various Islamic militant groups
last month to halt anti-government violence, he said this was a
unilateral act by the militant groups and his ministry has nothing
to do with it.
</P>
<P>
"Whoever wants a halt, let him do that...For us, all firmness
will be shown against whoever breaks the law and legitimacy,"
el-Alfy said.
</P>
<P>
On August 9, Sheikh Omar Abdel Rahman, spiritual leader of the
Islamic Group, known as Al Gamaa Islamiya in Arabic, announced
from his prison cell that he supports the peace initiative
forwarded by leading militants.
</P>
<P>
Since then, imprisoned leaders of a number of major militant
groups, including Gihad and Negoum Min Al Nar (Survivors of Hell),
have come out in support of the initiative. Militant leaders
abroad, however, have been reluctant to give definitive reactions.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the security bodies have managed to cut off
foreign financing for terrorist groups.
</P>
<P>
In August 1993, former Interior Minister Abdel Halim Moussa
lost his job after opening up dialogue with militant groups.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 1,190 people have been killed in Egypt since 1992 in a
wave of violence unleashed by militant fundamentalist groups in an
attempt to topple the secular rule. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
