<DOCNO> XIE19970907.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Background Materials for SADC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The Southern African
Development Community (SADC) was set up on August 17, 1992 by 10
countries which signed a treaty to replace the Southern African
Development Cooperation Conference (SADCC).
</P>
<P>
The SADCC was first held at Arusha, Tanzania in July 1979 to
harmonize development plans and to reduce the region's economic
dependence on South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The treaty has placed binding obligations on its member
countries, with the aim of promoting economic integration toward
a fully developed common market.
</P>
<P>
A tribunal was to be established to arbitrate in the case of
disputes between members states arising from the treaty. By
September 1993, all the 10 members such as Angola, Swaziland,
Botswana, Mozambique, Tanzania, Lesotho, Namibia, Zambia, Malawi
and Zimbabwe had ratified the treaty; it came into effect on
October 5.
</P>
<P>
South Africa and Mauritius have subsequently become members of
the SADC, and Seychelles and the Democratic Republic of Congo
have applied to join the regional group and their memberships
will be discussed at the summit to be held Monday.
</P>
<P>
The treaty declares the following aims:
</P>
<P>
1, deeper economic cooperation and integration, on the basis
of balance, equality and mutual benefit, providing for
cross-border investment and trade, and freer movement of factors
of production, goods and services across national boundaries;
</P>
<P>
2, common economic, political and social values and systems,
enhancing enterprise competitiveness, democracy and good
governance, respect for the rule of law and human rights, popular
participation, and the alleviation of poverty; and
</P>
<P>
3, strengthened regional solidarity, peace and security, in
order for the people of the region to live and work in harmony.
</P>
<P>
The summit meeting is held annually and is attended by Heads
of State and Government or their representatives. It is the
supreme policy-making organ of the SADC.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of SADC member states at ministerial level
meet at least twice a year; in addition, special meetings are
held to coordinate regional policy in a particular field by, for
example, ministers of energy and ministers of transport.
</P>
<P>
A conference with the SADC's "international cooperating
partners" or donor governments and international agencies is held
annually to review progress in the various sectors of the SADC
program and to present new projects requiring assistance.
</P>
<P>
the regional body's executive secretary is Kaire Mbuende, a
Namibian deputy agriculture minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970907.0107 </DOCNO>
