<HEADLINE> 10 Killed in Chartered Plane Crash in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Ten persons including
four foreigners on board a chartered plane which crashed in
Sarawak, East Malaysia, last night, were today confirmed all
killed, according to reports from Miri where the air crash
occurred.
</P>
<P>
The 19-seater Dornier 228 aircraft was on a regularly scheduled

flight for Miri from the Brunei capital Bandar Seri Begawan.
</P>
<P>
All the bodies were accounted for and they were being winched
from the site some 14 kilometers south of the Miri airport, the
reports said, quoting Sarawak Deputy Chief Minister George Chan as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The dead were identified as Inoue Tamiji (Japan) and Uemura
Sayuri (Japan), Kuek Loy Yeap (Singapore) and D.D. Mendis (Sri
Lanka), the rest were Malaysians.
</P>
<P>
"The aircraft broke into three pieces and was badly ripped in
the tail part. However, there seems to be no signs of an
explosion," Chan, who had an aerial inspection of the area, told
reporters in Miri.
</P>
<P>
Chan said the plane hit a few tree tops before slamming into
the slope midway up the hill at a height of 500 meters.
</P>
<P>
Rescuers who trekked for three hours through thick jungle
guided by villagers to reach the crash site on the slope of Lambir
hill found no survivors from the ill-fated flight B838.
</P>
<P>
Some 400 people took part in the rescue operation. They
comprised personnel from the police, army, fire and rescue
services, Royal Malaysian Air Force (RMAF), Civil Defense
Department and the Royal Brunei Air Force (RBAF).
</P>
<P>
Four helicopters -- one each from the RMAF and the RBAF and two
locally chartered -- participated in the search.  
</P>
</TEXT>
