<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Develops New Technique to Cure Sterility </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Israeli doctors have
developed a new technique to produce an implanted embryo by
"fishing" for individual sperm in the testicles of an infertile
man, The Jerusalem Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
A man, 29, who bears an extra female sex chromosome, and his
wife, 22, were overjoyed to learn Saturday that doctors viewed
the heartbeat of the six-week-old embryo that has been
successfully implanted in the woman's uterus.
</P>
<P>
The man suffers from Klinefelter's syndrome, an abnormal
condition of male sexual characteristics in which the body cells
contain one or more extra X chromosome. Normally, men have an X
and a Y sex chromosome.
</P>
<P>
The characteristics of the syndrome include infertility and
atrophied testicles, and the condition affects one out of 900
men. The more extra X chromosomes the person carries, the more
severe the abnormalities.
</P>
<P>
An in-vitro fertilization unit team, headed by Dr. Aby Lewin,
performed multiple fine-needle aspirations of the man's
testicles and found two sperms which were used to impregnate ripe
ova taken from his wife.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Dr. Lewin as saying that "ours is the first
clinical pregnancy resulting from the aspiration technique on an
infertile man with this syndrome."  
</P>
</TEXT>
