<HEADLINE> E. Africa Reaches Pact on Road Transport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda,
the three member states of the East African Cooperation (EAC),
have reached agreement on road transport in the region, the Daily
Nation newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
"The agreement seeks to harmonize various laws and practices
in the three states relating to market access, ports of entry,
routes authorized for international operations and transit
routes," Kenyan Attorney-General Amos Wako was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The accord also seeks to harmonize documentation procedures
relating to road transportation, taxes, fees and charges relevant
to immigration formalities, he said.
</P>
<P>
The pact is set to get ministerial consent at the ninth
meeting of the Commission for EAC in November, he said at the end
of EAC attorney-generals' meeting in Kenya's Indian Ocean port
Mombasa Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Participants also dwelt on EAC policy-making and common legal
and judicial operation so as to strengthen cooperation among the
three countries.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda and Burundi sent observers to the two-day meeting.
</P>
</TEXT>
