<HEADLINE> Plane Crashes in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 7 (Xinhua) -- A chartered Dornier 228
plane with 10 people on board crashed in Sarawak, East Malaysia,
last night, according to the Malaysian national news agency
Bernama today.
</P>
<P>
The fate of the two pilots and eight passengers on the plane,
which crashed in Lambir hill near Miri in the state, has yet to be
ascertained.
</P>
<P>
The two pilots and four of the eight passengers are Malaysians
and the other four passengers are two Japanese, one Singaporean
and one Sri Lankan, Bernama reported quoting a spokesman of the
Royal Brunei Airlines (RBA) which is the sales agent for the
chartered flight.
</P>
<P>
The ill-fated flight B1238 was from Bandar Seri Begawan,
Brunei, to Miri, a city in Sarawak, not far from Bandar Seri
Begawan.
</P>
<P>
The wreckage of the 19-seater plane was spotted at 7:10 a.m.
today and a rescue team from the Royal Malaysian Air Force (RMAF)
was despatched to the site.
</P>
<P>
Civilian helicopters have also been deployed to join in rescue
efforts.
</P>
<P>
Emergency teams and a Royal Brunei Armed Forces helicopter with
winching facilities have been despatched to the crash site as
well.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a spokesman of the Meteorological Department in
Kuching, capital of Sarawak, was quoted as saying that the weather
was fair in Miri Saturday with no heavy rain or thunderstorm
while the haze situation had improved with visibility being more
than 10 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The chartered Dornier plane crash is the sixth air crash in the
country since the beginning of this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
