<HEADLINE> Highway Extending Rapidly In Northeastern Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Liaoning
Province, one of the oldest and largest industrial bases in the
country, has made a rapid progress in its highway construction,
according to a recent local meeting on highways.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996, the province had more than 43,753 km of
highways, including 597 km expressways, increasing by 9.1 percent
and 53.9 percent over 1991 respectively.
</P>
<P>
During the Eighth Five-Year Plan (1991-1995) period, Liaoning
rebuilt 10,378 km bituminous roads -- a length equal to the total
of the previous seven Five-Year Plans.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, 73.6 per cent of local villages and towns have their
own tarred roads, and 93.6 percent of villages have bus service.
</P>
<P>
The province now has five freeways linking major cities
including Shenyang, the provincial capital, Dalian, a large port
city, Tieling and Bengxi, both heavy industrial bases, and Fushun, known
for its coal industry.
</P>
<P>
The fast expansion of highways has facilitated the local
economic development and has created better conditions for the
state-owned enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
