<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Busts International Drug Trafficking Racket </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The Indian police have
recently busted an international drug trafficking racket following
the arrest of five African nationals in Delhi and Bombay, the
local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
All the five, three Nigerians and two women from Burundi, were
deployed as couriers and found possessing 10 kilograms of heroin
worth over 100 million rupees (about 2.86 million U.S. dollars) in
the international market, police sources said.
</P>
<P>
The racket came to light when a woman, bound for Togo, was
caught at the Bombay airport early this week with 6.4 kilograms of
heroin concealed in the picture tube of a color TV.
</P>
<P>
Based on her interrogation, Delhi was alerted and a husband and
wife team were picked up later, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, a woman from Burundi was also
intercepted on September 2 and 2.61 kilograms of heroin recovered.
The drugs were concealed inside the covers of executive diaries,
folders and purses.
</P>
<P>
Sustained interrogation led to picking up of another national
from Burundi from a hotel room in south Bombay and recovery of one
kilogram of heroin.  
</P>
</TEXT>
