<HEADLINE> Hurricane Erika Moving off Northeastern Caribbean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Hurricane Erika grew
stronger today as it was moving off the northeastern Caribbean
with 140 kph winds and torrential rain.
</P>
<P>
Though many islands escaped the hurricane, officials in Puerto
Rico warned residents to expect heavy rain, coastal flooding and
beach erosion.
</P>
<P>
At 8 p.m. EDT, Erika was centered about 370 kilometers
east-northeast of San Juan. It was moving west-northwest with
winds about 140 kph.
</P>
<P>
Hurricane watches for Puerto Rico and the U.S. and British
Virgin Islands are expected to be lifted overnight. Warnings were
canceled Saturday afternoon for all other islands.
</P>
<P>
Following the hurricane warnings, businesses closed, shelters
opened, ferry services were halted and residents boarded up homes
and stocked up on rations on many islands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
