<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Number of Telephones Increases in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The number of telephones in
Myanmar increased to 195,494 at the end of August from 66,707 in
late 1988, The New Light of Myanmar reported today.
</P>
<P>
During the period, the number of channels also increased to
4,009, up from only 1,078.
</P>
<P>
In the past nine years, new auto-telephone exchanges have been
installed in states and divisions, with existing ones extended and
out-dated phones substituted with auto ones, the report said.
</P>
<P>
To promote the communication system as the national economy
develops, the Myanmar authorities have also installed micro-wave
links since 1995, connecting among states and divisions.
</P>
<P>
The digital micro-wave links, already installed in two recent
years, connected Myanmar's second largest city of Mandalay with
Lashio, Loikaw, Shwebo and Pakokku, it said.
</P>
<P>
Up to June this year, altogether 53 micro-wave stations had
been built, connecting the capital of Yangon with nine other
cities in the country, it said.
</P>
<P>
During the period, local satellite stations were built, linking
Yangon with 14 remote towns, and 64 ground stations for micro-wave
links are being under construction in the country.
</P>
<P>
These projects are expected to be completed over the next three
years. By then, direct dialing can be made for computer telegraph,
fax data and phone calls in 80 big towns and cities throughout the
14 states and divisions of Myanmar, the report added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
