<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Plans to Form Auto Conglomerates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 7 (Xinhua) -- China is considering propping
up its auto industry by forming three or four conglomerates
through restructuring, "China Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Each group should have the ability to produce at least 400,000
vehicles annually and earn at least 1.2 billion yuan in profits on
40 billion yuan in sales.
</P>
<P>
China has 123 automobile assembly plants, but 13 produce 90
percent of the industry's output, about 1.5 million units a year.
</P>
<P>
A Ministry of Machine Building Industry official stressed the
significance of achieving economies of scale, calling for
restructuring among the 13 large automakers.
</P>
<P>
The remaining plants could be transformed into parts suppliers
and subsidiaries to the auto giants or motor vehicle conversion
plants.
</P>
<P>
"The merger process is supposed to be handled through market
mechanism, rather than relying on the government to implement it,"
the official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
