<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Tap Mining Resources Abroad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 7 (Xinhua) -- China will encourage the mining
industry to invest abroad and explore foreign mining resources,
said today's China Daily Business Weekly.
</P>
<P>
In the next five years, the country aims to create three to
five large and medium mineral resource development bases, plus
several small bases or shareholding projects in Latin America,
Africa and bordering Asian countries, the newspaper reported
quoting sources from the Ministry of Geology and Mineral Resources.
</P>
<P>
China's annual demand for minerals in the next 20 years is
expected to grow five percent annually vs lower or negative
growth in identified reserves of most minerals.
</P>
<P>
With a mineral trade deficit of 10 billion US dollars, China is
the world's second largest mineral consumer and the third largest
importer, the mining ministry said.
</P>
<P>
According to the overseas mineral development plan, China will
create several mineral resource exploration teams focusing on
overseas business, including a large overseas mining corporation
and some small and medium mining firms.
</P>
<P>
The plan divides overseas mineral development into two stages.
During the 1997-2001 period, the government will draft laws to
regulate overseas mineral development. It also will select pilot
projects abroad.
</P>
<P>
At the second stage, 2002-2010, it will expand the scale of
overseas mineral development and create several overseas mineral
supply bases.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
