<HEADLINE> Italian FM to Meet U.S. Secretary of State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto
Dini will be in Washington Monday for talks with U.S. secretary of
State Madeline Albright on the eve of her first Mideast mission
since taking office in January.
</P>
<P>
How to revive the stalled Middle East peace talks will be on
top of the agenda of their meeting. Italy is also keen to play a
role in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Dini said Thursday that the peace process had been too slow in
recent months, leaving room for extremists to re-surface. He
called for greater efforts from Europe and the United States to
revive the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Albright, to begin her trip on September 9, will bring her
initiatives to help countries in the region resume dialogues. She
will travel to Israel, the Palestinian self-rule territories,
Syria, Jordan and possibly Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. secretary of state is reportedly trying to save the
stalled peace process after an Israeli decision to build 6,500
houses in the Arab East Jerusalem prompted several suicide bombing
attacks against Israel in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Also high on the agenda of the meeting will be the reform of
the United Nations Security Council ahead of a U.N. General
Assembly session in the autumn.
</P>
<P>
Dini said Italy believed reform should be based on the need to
uphold "the criteria of democracy and ample representation."
</P>
<P>
Dini and Albright will also discuss the situation in Albania
since the withdrawal of the Italy-led Multinational Protection
Force. 
</P>
