<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-South African Trade to Intensify After Diplomatic Normalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The trade and economic
cooperation between China and South Africa is expected to take off
after the two countries establish diplomatic ties in near future, said
today's Business Weekly of China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Although South Africa has grown into China's biggest trade
partner in Africa, the potential of bilateral economic ties has
not been fully tapped because of the absence of diplomatic ties,
said trade expert Tao Shui'e, a researcher with the Chinese Academy
of International Trade and Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
She said that the bilateral trade and economic cooperation
should increase after the normalization of bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Chris Dlamini, director of the South African Center for Chinese
Studies, said trade and investment protection agreements, which
normally are entered into by countries with diplomatic relations,
would be the basis for trade and economic cooperation between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
Dlamini said South Africa welcomed normalization of relations
with China and was willing to build substantive relations between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Tao said that with the expected most-favored nation treatment
and lower tariffs brought by trade agreement, bilateral trade will
increase remarkably. The most conservative prediction by Chinese
trade officials and experts set bilateral trade by the end of this
century at two billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The figure for this year will be about 1.3 to 1.4 billion US
dollars, about the same as last year, she said.
</P>
<P>
At present, the Chinese investment in South Africa totals 125
million US dollars, and that of South Africa in China is 60
million US dollars, according to the South African Center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
