<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Condemns Bombing Attacks in Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, September 6 (Xinhua) -- The Mexican government
today condemned the bombing attacks that occurred this week in
Cuba and expressed its solidarity with the people and the
government of that nation.
</P>
<P>
The Mexican Foreign Affairs Ministry said in a communique,
"Mexico rejects terrorism, no matter which reasons are stated to
try to justify it."
</P>
<P>
"Mexico expresses its indignation for the damage to lives and
property caused by acts of violence against that sister nation,"
it added.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, four bombs exploded in three hotels and a
restaurant in Havana, killing an Italian businessman. Bombings
also occurred in Cuba in July and August.
</P>
<P>
Mexico deplored "the injuries caused to innocent persons and
the death of Italian businessman Fabio Di Celmo," the communique
said.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Cuban National Assembly Speaker Ricardo Alarcon, who
was attending an international parliamentary conference in Chile,
said the bombing attacks were part of a plan hatched by U.S.-based
exile groups.
</P>
<P>
"They are trying to hurt the Cuban economy, to hit the tourism
industry because of its present importance," Alarcon said.
</P>
<P>
Recently, the Cuban government has been trying to boost the
country's economy by promoting tourism which has overtaken sugar
as Cuba's main hard currency-earning industry.
</P>
<P>
Alarcon also criticized the U.S. government for turning a blind
eye to the exile groups that violently oppose the current Cuban
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
