<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT September 7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA -- Two Canadian scientists have discovered that wetlands
and ponds in the province of Saskatchewan have one of the highest
concentrations of viruses in the world.
</P>
<P>
The count of 2.5 billion viruses per milliliter of water
astounded the two scientists, said a report Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Richard Robarts of Environment Canada's National Hydrology
Research Institute and Prof. David Bird of the University of
Quebec said that more research is required to determine the nature
of viruses.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel has been tightening its siege on
Palestinian self-rule areas and arrested more Palestinians inside
the Palestinian territories, the Jerusalem Media and Communication
Center (JMCC) reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli troops set up road blocks at the entrances of
Palestinian cities, towns, villages and refugee camps on the third
day of the total closure re-imposed on Palestinian territories
following three explosions in Jerusalem Thursday, the JMCC said.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey announced here Saturday that the Turkish
troops will not participate in the planned NATO naval exercises in
the Aegean and eastern Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
"The decision has been taken not to take part in the Dynamic
Mix-97 NATO exercises," the Turkish Foreign Ministry said in a
written statement.
</P>
<P>
"The main reason for this decision is the concessions given by
some NATO military authorities to Greece in order to convince it
to join the exercise," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
YAOUNDE -- A bill to amend certain provisions of the law
governing Cameroun's presidencial elections was adopted by the
National assembly Friday.
</P>
<P>
The bill was examined by the Costitutional Laws Committee and
adopted by the majority parliamentarians at the plenary session of
the national assembly.
</P>
<P>
The bill was adopted in the absence of parliamentarians of the
major opposition party, Social Democratic Front (SDF), which
staged a walkout during dileberations to protest against the draft
report of the bill, which is said to be compiled without concerns
of the SDF parliamentarians in the Constitutional Laws Committee.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- The funeral of Britain's Princess Diana was held
Saturday morning in London's Westminster Abbey, with millions of
mourners bidding farewell to the Princess.
</P>
<P>
Queen Elizabeth II, Diana's former husband Prince Charles, her
sons Princes William and Harry, and other members of the royal
family and Diana's family joined the 1,900 people attending the
funeral service inside the abbey.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- Forty-nine civilians were massacred and about 60
injured Friday night, presumably by Islamic extremists, in Beni
Messous near the Algerian capital Algiers, Agence France-Presse
(AFP) reported.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said that an armed commando of Islamic militants
descended on the village of Sidi Youssef and slaughtered the
villagers with axes and other agricultural tools.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that the mutilated bodies of the victims were
assembled on the ground of a hospital in Beni Messous.
</P>
<P>
This is the worst massacre to have taken place near the
Algerian capital since Algeria was plunged into violence in 1992
after the army cancelled an election victory won by Islamists.
</P>
</TEXT>
