<HEADLINE> Davenport/Novotna Win Women's Doubles at U.S. Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Lindsay Davenport of the
United States combined with Jana Novotna of the Czech Republic to
win the women's doubles final at the U.S. Open tennis tournament
here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Davenport and Novotna, seeded third, claimed their first Grand
Slam title with a 6-3, 6-4 victory over Natasga Zvereva of
Belarus and Gigi Fernandez of the United States in 75 minutes at
Arthur Ashe Stadium.
</P>
<P>
Davenport and Novotna were playing together for the 10th time
and had never before advanced to the semi-finals in a major as a
team.
</P>
<P>
However, top-seeded Zvereva and Fernandez have, as one of the
all-time great doubles teams, won 14 major titles -- three U.S.
Opens, five French Opens, two Australian Opens and four
Wimbledons.
</P>
<P>
Fernandez, who has won 68 doubles titles in her career,
including 17 Grand Slam crowns with partners including Novotna
and Martina Navratilova, announced after the match that she would
retire from doubles at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
The 33-year-old American has won the French Open and Wimbledon
titles this season with Zvereva.
</P>
<P>
Zvereva, 26, was seeking an individual Grand Slam this year
after winning the Australian Open with Martina Hingis before
renewing her partnership with Fernandez. 
</P>
</TEXT>
