<HEADLINE> Rafter, Rusedski Advance to U.S. Open Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Australian 13th seed Patrick
Rafter upset second-seeded American Michael Chang in straight
sets and Greg Rusedski of Britain outlasted Sweden's Jonas
Bjorkman in five sets, both reaching the final of the 10.12
million U.S. dollars U.S. Open here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Rafter, who had never been past the third round in this
tournament, spoiled Chang's dream of winning his first U.S. Open
title with a 6-3, 6-3, 6-4 victory.
</P>
<P>
The 24-year-old Rafter, who became the first Australian to
reach the U.S. Open final since Ken Rosewall in 1974, routed
Chang with 52 winners in the two-hour, two minutes victory. He
rushed the net 90 times to force the action against Chang.
</P>
<P>
The 14th ranked Rafter, who has been in five finals this year
without a victory, will meet unseeded Rusedski in Sunday's final.
</P>
<P>
Rusedski advanced earlier with a 6-1, 3-6, 3-6, 6-3, 7-5
semi-final victory over unseeded Swede Jonas Bjorkman.
</P>
<P>
Rusedski is the first British male to reach a Grand Slam
singles final since John Lloyd, who lost in the final of the 1977
Australian Open to Vitas Gerulaitis.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the third-seeded team of Lindsay Davenport of the
United States and Jana Novotna of the Czech Republic upset top
seeds Gigi Fernandez of the United States and Natasha Zvereva of
Belarus, 6-3, 6-4, to win the women's doubles championship.
</P>
</TEXT>
