<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ottawa Not to Compel Crown Firms to Obey New Ethics Code </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 6 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government
endorses but won't require its Crown corporations to obey a new
international code of business practices and ethics, said reports
today.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Affairs Minister Lloyd Axworthy said that like at other
companies, the managers of Crown corporations will decide for
themselves whether to adopt the code, because it is voluntary.
</P>
<P>
Ottawa will not require federal Crown corporations to adopt the
code. Nor will private companies receiving federal export
assistance be required to adopt the code.
</P>
<P>
Though the code is voluntary, Axworthy expressed the belief
that Canadian companies will want to act ethically and support
human rights in the countries where they operate.
</P>
<P>
The new code, drafted by a group of Canadian companies and
associations with foreign operations, was published today.
</P>
<P>
It commits companies that participate to a set of principles on
how they will operate overseas. The code is similar to the one
adopted recently by several U.S. companies.
</P>
<P>
Among the new code's provisions are promises to:
</P>
<P>
-- promote human rights in areas where companies have
influence;
</P>
<P>
-- refrain from paying bribes or engaging in corrupt business
practices;
</P>
<P>
-- protect worker health and safety; and
</P>
<P>
-- shun child labor and protect the environment.
</P>
<P>
It also says companies will promote social justice and allow
workers freedom of speech and association in the workplace.
</P>
<P>
Yet, it stops short of saying workers can form their own labor
unions.
</P>
<P>
Among companies signing the code are Canadian Occidental
Petroleum Ltd., Alcan Aluminum Ltd., Cambior Inc., Chauvco
Resources Ltd. and Shell Canada Ltd.
</P>
<P>
Business associations supporting the code include the Business
Council on National Issues, the Alliance of Manufacturers and
Exporters Canada, the Canadian Chamber of Commerce and the
Conference Board of Canada. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970907.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Simitis Stresses Importance of Meeting Economic Targets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 6 (Xinhua) -- A failure to meet economic
targets set for the next two years would jeopardize Greece's
efforts to enter the European Union's mainstream, Greek Prime
Minister Costas Simitis said today.
</P>
<P>
"Remaining countries in the European Union (EU) are moving
ahead. The repercussions of a delay beyond 1999 would be highly
dangerous, and we are not going to play with the country's fate,"
Simitis said in his annual economic policy speech at this year's
Thessaloniki international trade fair.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that 1998 was an especially critical turning point
and Greece had difficult and pressing targets that the country had
to achieve simultaneously in two years at the most.
</P>
<P>
Consumer price inflation, he said, had to drop below 3 percent
in 1998, sinking to 2 percent a year later.
</P>
<P>
Although the Greek government had managed to cut inflation to
5.5 percent from 8.5 percent a year ago, tight fiscal and monetary
policies had to stay in place in order to drive it down further,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Greece's fiscal deficit had to drop below 3 percent of the
gross domestic product (GDP) in 1998, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said the rate of GDP growth, estimated at 3.5 percent for
1997, was forecast to rise to 4 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Greek government also planned to bring about structural
reforms by increasing competitiveness through investments,
creating better conditions to tackle inflation, ensuring jobs by
investing in infrastructure and manpower, and by wide-ranging
administrative reforms, Simitis said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
