<DOCNO> XIE19970907.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ottawa to Spend Money on Youth Internships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Canada's federal government
will spend 90 million dollars (65 million US dollars) during the
next three years to create 1,000 public-service internships for
young Canadians.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Jean Chretien is expected to announce the
initiative Monday, two weeks before the new parliament opens, said
a report today.
</P>
<P>
The move is designed to illustrate that assisting young people
in their search for work will be one of the top priorities of the
re-elected Liberal government.
</P>
<P>
Canada's youth unemployment rate has been notoriously high in
recent years. It stood at 16.7 percent in August, compared with an
overall jobless rate of 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Chretien's government was constantly attacked in June's federal
election for failing to improve the employment of Canadian youths.
</P>
<P>
In February, the government announced a two-year, 225 million
dollar (162 million US dollar) plan to finance youth internships.
</P>
<P>
But demands were such that the funding for this year is close
to being exhausted after just a few months.
</P>
<P>
Chretien is expected to make the announcement after a meeting
in Toronto with senior executives involved in a private-sector
youth employment initiative. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
